[[File:Tsuki-jinja (Saitama) entrance.JPG|thumb|right|{{Center|Precinct entrance}}{{Small|There is no torii gate, and a {{jalink|shimenawa|Q1887421}} is strung in its place. There are rabbits on both sides. }}]]'''Cho Shrine'' (Tsukijinja{{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}) is located in (Saitama City)|Q11476004|Kishimachi}} {{jalink|Shrine|Q845945}} located in 3-chome. {{jalink|Shikinaisha}} and {{jalink|Modern company rank system|Q712534|Old company rank}} is {{jalink|Prefectural company}}.

Another name is ``Tsukinomiya''. Due to the ``Tsuki'' in the company name, there has been a belief in waiting for the moon since ancient times, and the shrine is known for having a guardian rabbit instead of {{jalink|guardian dog|Q20155846}}.

=== Enshrined God ===
The following three deities are enshrined. </ref>.
* {{jalink|Amaterasu Omikami|Q455602|Amaterasu Omikami}} (Amaterasu Omikami)
* {{jalink|Toyoukebime|Q2983724|Toyoukebime no Mikoto}}
* {{jalink|Susanoo|Q272993|Susanoo}}

As a legend about the enshrined deity, one of the Seven Wonders ({{jalink|#Seven Wonders||described later}}) that has been handed down at Cho Shrine since ancient times is that there is no pine tree. According to the legend, there was an older sister god and a younger brother god in this area, but the younger god went to Omiya, and even though the older sister god was waiting for her to return, the younger brother didn't come back, so the older sister god didn't want to wait anymore. The older sister and younger gods that appear in this legend are said to correspond to Amaterasu Omikami (our company's enshrined deity) and Sujinson (Omiya's {{jalink|Hikawa Shrine|Q703633}} enshrined deity).According to other literature, the enshrined deity is {{jalink|Seoritsuhime|Q13579836|Seoritsuhima}}.{{efn|``{{jalink|Nihon Sokoku Fudoki}}'' includes the entry ``Enshrined Place Festival{{jalink|Seoritsuhime|Q13579836|Seoritsuhima}}ya''. }}, the theory that it is Chogyoku-no-Mikoto <ref>``Musashikuni Shikinai Shijushi-jinja Shrine Meituke''</ref>, the theory that it is {{jalink|Tsukiyomi-no-Mikoto}} {{efn|``{{jalink|Edo Famous Places Encyclopedia|Q2704637}}'' is listed as ``Enshrined deity, {{jalink|Tsukiyomi no Mikoto}} Ichiza, Honji {{jalink|Seishi Bosatsu|Q1465683}}'' in our company's entry. }}, the theory that there are two pillars, the god of the sun and {{jalink|Uganomitama||Kura Inari Tama no Mikoto}}{{efn|``{{jalink|New version of Musashi Fudoki manuscript|Q11503943}} '', our company's section states, ``Our company is the place where the two shrines of the god of the sun, {{jalink|Uganomitama||Kura Inari Tama no Mikoto}}, are enshrined.'' Kishimura, Adachi District}}. }}, the theory that there are two pillars: {{jalink|Amaterasu Omikami|Q455602}} and {{jalink|Uganomitama||Ugaomitama}}<ref>{{jalink|Atsutane Hirata|Q2572749}} His works included ``Cho Shrine Research'' and ``{{jalink|Specially Selected Names of Gods|Q11571092}}''</ref>.

=== History ===

=== Founding ===According to the company records (``Chogu Engi'' written in {{jalink|Kanbun|Q1146228}} 8th year ({{jalink|1668|Q7595}}), it was founded as a dedication shrine in March 1996 by the 9th {{jalink|Emperor Kaika|Q333548}}. Also, at the time of the 10th Emperor Sujin, {{jalink|Emperor Sujin|Q333530}}, {{jalink|Wahime no Mikoto|Q4388732}, the chief priest of {{jalink|Ise Grand Shrine|Q687168}} }} visited the area, chose this area as a clean hill, and built a storehouse to store the offerings (tributes and offerings) to be presented to the Ise Grand Shrine. {{jalink|Kazusa Province|Q1055394|Kazusa}}・{{jalink|Shimousa Province|Q1053695|Shimousa}}・{{jalink|Awa Province|Q1053044|Awa}} , {{jalink|Ueno country|Q1054838|Ueno}}, {{jalink|Shimono country|Q1053699|Shimono}}), that is, it is determined to be the first-crop rice and tono collection center in the Kanto region. Furthermore, {{jalink|Hoki|Q18520676}}2 years ({{jalink|771 years|Q29950}}) {{jalink|June 20th (Lunar calendar)|Q839899|On June 20th}}, Fujiwara no Ason Tsunetoki held a dedication as {{jalink|Imperial envoy|Q11399920}}, so this was the regular festival (currently the new calendar {{ jalink|July 20th|Q2728}}) is said to have originated from {{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Shikinai Shrine)|1976}}{{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Gods)|1984}}<ref name="Explanation board"/>.The authenticity of the above tradition is uncertain, but since ``cho'' can be seen in the company name in the ``Shikinai-sha Investigation Report,'' etc., {{jalink|Imperial court (Japan)|Q30253177|It is assumed that the okura, where the offerings (tributes and gifts) to the Imperial Court}} were deposited, became the predecessor of Cho Shrine. A related legend is that one of the seven wonders of Cho Shrine is the absence of torii gates, and it is said that this is due to the removal of the torii gates and shrine gates that obstructed the transportation of treasures on the orders of {{jalink|Wahime no Mikoto|Q4388732}}, and this legend also indicates that the predecessor of Cho Shrine was Mikura.{{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Shikinai Shrine)|1976}}. And in the second year of Houki (771), when it is said that there was a dedication ceremony, the affiliation of {{jalink|Musashi Province|Q907398}} changed from {{jalink|Tosando|Q1334011}} to {{jalink|Tokaido| Since it has been changed to Q1196306}}, <ref> "{{jalink|Shoku Nihongi|Q611399}}" October 2nd year of Houki (771) {{jalink|Kiu|Q1062557}} (27th) article. </ref>It is speculated that the actual founding of the shrine was when Ogura, which had ceased to be a place where Chomono could pass through due to this road change, was considered sacred and was dedicated as a shrine.Apart from the above, there is also a theory that it was dedicated by the Choren, Choshu, Chokishi, and Choi-sun clans (Cho clan) that appear in ``{{jalink|Newly Selected Surnames and Records|Q1045362}}'' and {{jalink|Rokukokushi|Q1151168|Kokushi}}. This Cho clan is an immigrant clan, and it has been pointed out that it is related to the fact that there are many {{jalink|immigrants|Q11561926}} living in groups in Togoku. Our company's location name "{{jalink|Kishimachi (Saitama City)|Q11476004|Kishi}}" is said to be derived from "{{jalink|Koshishi|Q55526932}}" {{Sfn|Kishimura (Heibonsha)|2004}}. In addition, there is a theory that associates the Japanese zelkova tree ({{jalink|zelkova|Q920344}}), which is often found in the temple grounds, with "tone"<ref>{{jalink|Kokugaku|Q855159 }}'s {{jalink|Harumura Kurokawa|Q6536184}} has a theory that ``There is an old Japanese tsuki tree called tsuki in the whole area of the shrine.Therefore, I think the key is a borrowed character for tsuki.'' </ref>Also {{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Great Dictionary of Shinto)|1941}}.

=== Outline ===
[[File:NDL-DC 1310959 Utagawa Kunisada Urawa Chonosha/Aburaya Okon crd.jpg|thumb|{{jalink|Utagawa Kunisada|Q467427}} Kiso Rokujuku's "Uragawa Chonosha/Aburaya Okon" (1852, 5th year of Kaei era)]]
{{jalink|extension (Era name)|Q1327274|Extended}} "{{jalink|Engishiki|Q1342448}}" established in 5 years ({{jalink|927|Q30470}}) {{jalink|Engishiki divine name book|Q11064932|God name book}} So, in {{jalink|Musashi Province|Q907398}}{{jalink|Adachi District|Q11637033}}, "Cho Shrine" is written, and it is listed as {{jalink|Shikiuchi Shrine}}{{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1976}}.

From {{jalink|Middle Ages|Q12554}}, since ``cho'' has the same reading as ``moon'', it has come to be associated with the belief in waiting for the moon.{{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}. {{jalink|Nobugen|Q1194159}}2nd year/{{jalink|Kenmu (Japan)|Q1193970|Kenmu}} In the 4th year ({{jalink|1337|Q6039}}), the shrine was reconstructed by {{jalink|Isshiki Noriyuki}} on the orders of {{jalink|Takauji Ashikaga|Q297107}}, but {{jal ink|Tensho|Q1145058}}It is said that it was burnt down by military fire during the {{jalink|Odawara Conquest|Q2622890}} in 18 years ({{jalink|1590|Q6764}}) {{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}.In {{jalink|Edo period|Q184963}}, {{jalink|Keian|Q1146135}} 2nd year ({{jalink|1649|Q6945}}), {{jalink|Tokugawa Iemitsu|Q314481}} donated 7 stones of {{jalink|shuinchi}}. This red stamp letter says ``Tsukuyomisha,'' {{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}, but in "Chogu Engi" this company name is written incorrectly. However, this company name continues to be used in subsequent shuinjo.

{{jalink|Betto-ji|Q11396755}} is Gassan-dera Temple, and {{jalink|Gyokuzo-in (Saitama City)|Q18336826|Gyokuzo-in}} was also attached to it. A twenty-three night hall was built in Gassan-ji Temple, and the {{jalink|Seishi Bosatsu|Q1465683}} of {{jalink|Getten|Q1061795|Tsukitenshi}} was enshrined as {{jalink|principal image|Q11520160}} {{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}.It is also listed in "{{jalink|Edo Meisho Zue|Q2704637}}," and many writers, writers, and artists also visit it, perhaps knowing about the god of Tsukimachi and Tsukuyomi. Among them, {{jalink|Kansei|Q1195131}} 3rd year ({{jalink|1791|Q7784}}) {{jalink|April 11th (Lunar Calendar)|Q838941|April 11th}}, the haiku poet {{jalink|Issa Kobayashi|Q312709}} wrote in his ``Kiko'' (Volume 5 of Issa's Complete Works) that he put his forehead to the ``Tsukiyomi no Miya'' located in the deep forest. In addition, {{jalink|Tsuda Daijo}}, a monk who loved traveling, wrote ``20 The shrine, which is called Sanya no Miya (omitted), has been constructed with great care and beauty, and the interior is decorated with so much heart and soul that it is filled with offerings that will astound your eyes if you wander into the middle of nowhere.'' {{Sfn|Saitama Shrines (Saitama Prefectural Shrine Agency)|1998}} Also, {{jalink|Culture (era name)|Q1373146|Bunka}}4 years ({{jalink|1807|Q6909}}) to {{jalink|Tenpo|Q1369045}}5 years ({{jalink|1834|Q759 1}}), the Tokugawa {{jalink|Shimizu family}} traveled to the suburbs of {{jalink|Edo|Q215646}} and visited {{jalink|Hiroshiki Yonin|Q11485425}}'s {{jalink|village}. In his records, Yasushi Omasa}} (whose name was Karyo) said, ``It is said to be a forest of {{jalink|Seishi Bosatsu|Q1465683}}.The head office and the hall of worship all have copper-roofed roofs, and the entire building is {{jalink|vermilion|Q737438| The structure of the shrine, which is painted vermilion and surrounded by azure (omitted), is not Buddhist, so it is likely that in ancient times it was worshiped as a god, but later it was worshiped as a Buddha.''<ref>Karyo Murao writes about the situation at that time. Author: Translated by Takatsugu Abe, “Edo Suburbs Roadside Signs: Modern Language Translation” {{jalink|Kodansha Academic Library|Q11632220}}, 2013. </ref>.In the 10th year of Tenpo ({{jalink|1839|Q7616}}), {{jalink|Atsutane Hirata|Q2572749}}, a {{jalink|Kokugaku|Q855159}} scholar, visited our company and wrote about the ``Chojinsha.'' In that book, we wrote that the shrine developed from a warehouse to store {{jalink|firstfruits|Q11396544}} to be delivered to {{jalink|Ise Jingu|Q687168}}.

After {{jalink|Meiji Restoration|Q8707}}, in {{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}}6 ({{jalink|1873|Q7757}}), {{jalink|Modern company ranking system|Q In 712534}}, it was ranked as {{jalink|gosha|Q134917316}}, and in 1898|Q7848}} it was promoted to {{jalink|kensha}}.

=== Precincts ===
The shrine building is {{jalink|Gongen-zukuri|Q3155268}}, with the main shrine and worship hall integrated, and was constructed in {{jalink|Ansei|Q1327259}}5 ({{jalink|1858|Q7684}}) {{Sfn|Cho Shrine (Heibonsha)|2004}}. The old main hall that was used until then is still used as the main hall of Inari Shrine within the shrine grounds.

In addition, the shrine grounds within the shrine grounds form a forest of old Zelkova and Mukunoki trees, and have been designated as a natural monument by Saitama City as the ``Cho Shrine Precincts Forest.''
