=== Seven Wonders ===
At Cho Shrine, the following seven wonders are handed down.
# No torii gate
#: It is said that on the orders of {{jalink|Wahime no Mikoto|Q4388732}}, the shrine gates and torii gates, which were obstacles to the transportation of preparations, were removed.
# No pine trees
#: It is said that this name originates from the fact that there was an older sister god and a younger brother god in this area, but eventually the younger god went to Omiya and did not come back even though the older sister was waiting for him, so the older sister said that she did not want to wait any longer. It is also said that he was poked in the eye by a pine tree in the shrine grounds while his sister deity was waiting for him.
# If you release a fish into Mitarai Pond (also known as Gourd Pond, which is now extinct), the fish will have one eye.
# The rabbit is {{jalink|divine messenger|Q10444973}}
# {{jalink|Nichiren|Q311478|Nichiren Saint}}Zelkova connecting pieces
#: It is said that Nichiren, who was exiled to {{jalink|Sado Island|Q998623}}, tied a piece to a zelkova tree to pray for a safe birth for a woman there who was suffering from difficult childbirth.
# No flies
# No mosquitoes

=== Local information ===
; Location
* {{jalink|Saitama Prefecture|Q128186}}{{jalink|Saitama City|Q134635}}{{jalink|Urawa Ward|Q1154583}}{{jalink|Kishimachi (Saitama City)|Q11476004|Kishimachi}}3-17-25

; Transportation access
* Railway: {{jalink|East Japan Railway|Q499071}} (JR East)<!--{{jalink|Keihin Tohoku Line|Q1197028}} and other lines--About a 10-minute walk from the west exit of "{{jalink|Urawa Station|Q652141}}".

; around
* Tsukinomiya Koen
*: A park adjacent to the precincts of Cho Shrine and owned by Saitama City. In January of {{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}}6 ({{jalink|1873|Q7757}}), the Grand Jokan of the Meiji government, which launched the park system as part of its modernization policy, established parks in each prefecture at famous sites and old ruins, such as within the precincts of temples and shrines. In February 1874, permission was granted to establish it as Urawa Park, and on December 12 of the same year, it was established as Urawa Park Kairakuen, the prefecture's first park. As a famous spot for cherry blossoms, the ``Sakura Festival'' is held in spring.
* {{jalink|Saitama Prefectural Route 213 Kyokumoto Saitama Line|Q11426912}}*: A road that passes through the west side of the shrine grounds. {{jalink|Shirahata (Saitama City)|Q17216551|Shirahata}}Intersection - In front of the shrine - {{jalink|Urawa Station|Q652141}} West exit intersection is the corner of {{jalink|Nakasendo|Q1154479}}, one of the {{jalink|Five Highways|Q1195921}}. It follows the original route, and the nickname ``Old Nakasendo'' is still used today (``Old'' is added because {{jalink|National Route 17|Q1057683}} was later opened in parallel). North from the vicinity of the shrine is {{jalink|Urawa-juku|Q3552142}}.

